---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="About Soundings">
  <article class="about">
    <header class="about-header">
      <h2>About Soundings</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Soundings is an MCP server wrapping a curated set of UK open data
        sources behind a small surface of question-shaped tools. Ask about a
        place — postcode, council, region — and get coherent answers grounded
        in named sources.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h3>How capture works</h3>
      <p>
        Every interaction with the server is logged as a structured record,
        with your consent. The published corpus becomes a public artefact in
        its own right under CC BY 4.0.
      </p>
      <ul class="consent-list">
        <li>
          <strong>Full consent</strong> — your question text and self-declared
          sector are captured. The text is sanitised before publication
          (postcodes truncated to sector, personal names redacted via NER,
          small-charity names stripped).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Minimal consent (default)</strong> — only the structured
          fields are captured: which tool was called, the place, the indicators
          returned. Your question text is never stored.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No consent</strong> — nothing is captured. You can still use
          the server.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Change your choice any time using the banner at the top of every page.
        The chosen level applies to the rest of your session.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>The corpus</h3>
      <p>
        Every month a sanitised snapshot of the question corpus is published
        as gzipped CSV and JSON Lines. The manifest records SHA-256 hashes,
        the catalogue version, the sanitisation rules version, and the git
        commit that produced it — so you can audit exactly what went in.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Phase 2 plan defers pushing the corpus to a hosted bucket; v1
        writes local artefacts only. See
        <a href="https://github.com/dataforaction-tom/soundings/blob/main/docs/adr/0004-corpus-publication.md">
          ADR-0004
        </a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>The data behind every answer</h3>
      <p>
        Every page that shows indicator values also shows the SourceRef for
        each one: where it came from, when we retrieved it, and what cache
        status it has. A collapsed "data behind this" panel shows the raw
        tool call and response so you can see what the UI saw.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Compare and trend</h3>
      <p>
        Each place page sparkline-charts the trend for any indicator whose
        source publishes a time series, so you can see direction and recent
        change alongside the latest value. The <a href="/compare">/compare</a>
        page accepts a comma-separated list of places and indicators and
        ranks each highlighted place against the full same-type peer
        universe — percentile by default, with rank, absolute, and rate
        bases also available.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Civil society</h3>
      <p>
        Place pages also show the registered charities operating in that area
        and the grants they've received in the last twelve months. The
        organisations come from the Charity Commission's monthly register
        (England &amp; Wales) and Find That Charity (Scotland &amp; Northern
        Ireland); the grants come from
        <a href="https://www.threesixtygiving.org/">360Giving</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h3>Links</h3>
      <ul class="link-list">
        <li>
          <a href="https://github.com/dataforaction-tom/soundings">GitHub</a>
          — source and spec
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://github.com/dataforaction-tom/soundings/blob/main/docs/v1-orchestration-and-capture.md">
            v1 orchestration &amp; capture spec
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          Corpus downloads — via <code>make publish-corpus</code> or the
          publication CLI
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .about-header {
    padding-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xl);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  .about-header h2 {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-md) 0;
    font-size: var(--font-size-3xl);
  }
  .lead {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--font-size-lg);
    color: var(--color-text-light);
    line-height: var(--line-height-relaxed);
  }
  .about section {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xl);
  }
  .about section h3 {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-md) 0;
    padding-bottom: var(--space-sm);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
    display: inline-block;
  }
  .about p {
    line-height: var(--line-height-relaxed);
  }
  .consent-list li,
  .link-list li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
    line-height: var(--line-height-relaxed);
  }
  .about code {
    font-family: ui-monospace, "SF Mono", Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background: var(--color-bg);
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);
  }
</style>
